FIG. 1a illustrates a perspective view of one embodiment of a subterranean termite detector with two upper signal ports and a plurality of lateral ingress/egress ports in communication with the signal ports;


FIG. 1b illustrates a perspective view of a further embodiment of a subterranean termite detector with one upper signal port, a plurality of lateral ingress/egress ports in communication with the signal ports, and having an external coating of corrosion-resistant termite impregnable material;


FIG. 1c illustrates a perspective view of a probe used to remove the seal created by termites across the signal port of the subterranean termite detector;


FIG. 2 illustrates an exploded perspective view of one embodiment of a subterranean termite concentrator/feeder combination enclosed laterally by a durable casing, and open on the dorsal and ventral surfaces;


FIG. 3 illustrates an exploded perspective view of a further embodiment of a subterranean termite concentrator/feeder combination enclosed laterally as in FIG. 2, but further including a concentrator dorsal cap, a concentrator/feeder ventral cap, a director assembly, a concentrator bait mass barrier and a supportive feeder receiver casing;


FIG. 4a illustrates an exploded perspective view of one embodiment of a feeder assembly having a bait mass enclosed laterally in a durable casing with its dorsal and ventral surfaces open;


FIG. 4b illustrates an exploded perspective view of a further embodiment of a feeder assembly featuring two separate bait masses and dorsal and ventral end caps to provide for tamper resistance;


FIG. 5 illustrates a plan view of a hypothetical residential plot containing a residential structure, a wood privacy fence, a detached shed, a wood pile, and several trees, around which detectors and concentrator/feeders of the present invention have been placed in accordance with the instructions provided herein; and


FIG. 6 illustrates a perspective view of an alternative subterranean termite detector according to a second preferred embodiment of the present invention.
